'''LXQ''' ('''Liquid eXtraction Quotient''') is a unit that defines the properties of a solid-liquid , specifically measuring the energy required to separate no less than 90% of the solid from the liquid, per 1  unit of mass. The precise details of this method is the commercially sensitive property of  Company; they have not released any technical information to the wider scientific community.
According to , LXQ is used in the research and development of effective new spill-proof delivery devices for certain types of chemicals and .